      "writtenOn": "2026-03-09T09:46:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, you are right. What we usualy do for these kinds of allocation is use a rbh_sstack. This is a custom allocator in robinhood where you can append memory dynamically at the end and free everything at once. The idea is that you use it to allocate memory as you need in each iteration. Then at then end you release everything. But this memory is used outside of the iterator, so you actually need to release it on the next call to the iterator\u0027s next function (otherwise this is a use-after-free kind of situation). So the pattern would be:\n\n```\nvoid *myiter_next(void *)\n{\n    // free what was allocated on the previous iteration\n    rbh_sstack_clear(iter-\u003esstack); // or rbh_sstack_pop_all\n\n    // then you can allocate new stuff on the sstack\n    // return what has been allocated for the caller to use\n}\n```\n\nYou also need to free the remaining memory when the iterator is destroyed.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 37
      },
      "revId": "9ae473bcb91b9cd5fb12f9ca795865c614562f18",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "15f04f0b_df6d0790",
